0.body: Estimated time to complete: 10 minutes This survey is designed to gather the opinions of Rust developers about a new feature for the Rust language. Your feedback will help the Rust compiler developers weigh between different design choices.
0.title: RPITIT Survey

1.body: First, we would like to know a little about you. How many years of experience do you have with Rust? Which of the following best describes you? I maintain Rust libraries used by many developers. I maintain small Rust libraries, but I mostly write application code. I only write Rust applications. I don't write much Rust code.
1.title: Demographics

2.title: Scenario

3.body:
Say that Will's intention as the library author is that "a personal shelf's available books are always exactly as listed in its books vector" is a public part of the specification for PersonalShelf::available_books. Say that Maryyann is an API client of books and wants to use the knowledge that PersonalShelf::available_books returns an ExactSizeIterator, like this: // my-library/main.rs use books::PersonalShelf; fn main() { let shelf = PersonalShelf { books: vec!["War and Peace".into(), "The Rust Programming Language".into()] }; assert_eq!(shelf.available_books().len(), 2);
} In this situation, everything is good — Will expects that Maryyann can call shelf.available_books().len(), and Maryyann is able to do so.
3.title: The Good Situation

4.body:
Now say that Will's intention as a library author is different. Will wrote PersonalShelf::available_books to return ExactSizeIterator solely for internal testing purposes. Will likes to write return types as specific as possible to catch problems when implementations change. But he did not intend for Maryyann to be able to rely on this detail. After publishing v0.1.0 of books, he later updates the implementation of PersonalShelf::available_books to filter accidental empty strings, like this: // books/lib.rs impl PersonalShelf { pub fn available_books(&self) -> impl Iterator<Item = &String> { self.books.iter().filter(|title| title != "") }
} Will thinks this is a non-breaking change and publishes v0.1.1. Maryyann runs cargo update, which updates travel v0.1.0 -> v0.1.1. Then Maryyann runs cargo check and her code has broken, because shelf.available_books() does not have a method .len(). This situation is bad because Will didn't realize he was making a breaking change. He violated the rules of semantic versioning, and wasted some of Maryyann's time.
4.title: The Bad Situation

5.title: An Alternative

6.body: To establish some terms, let's call this general problem the issue of "trait refinement". The original scenario presents a strategy where Rust does "implicit refinement" — Will writes a more specific type in the trait implementation, and any API client can use the more specific type. The alternative scenario presents a strategy where Rust does "explicit refinement" — Will can only write a more specific type if he adds the #[refine] keyword. You have seen the good and bad of implicit refinement in a hypothetical scenario. The good is that API clients can use the details of an implementation without any extra work from the API author. The bad is that the API author might not always be aware of which details are public, leading to semver hazards. Now, we want you to reflect on your own Rust experience. When would these kinds of situations arise in the libraries you use or maintain? With that in mind, please answer the following questions. There is no correct answer — we just want your intuition based on your Rust experience. 1. On balance, do you think trait refinement should be implicit or explicit? Implicit Explicit 2. Do you think Rust should use the #[refine] mechanism for trait refinement? Yes, Rust should use #[refine] for trait refinement No, Rust should not use #[refine] for trait refinement 3. Which of the following best describes your answers to Questions 1 and 2? Trait refinement should be explicit and #[refine] seems like a reasonable mechanism for it Trait refinement should be explicit, but I would prefer a different mechanism than #[refine] for refinement Trait refinement should be implicit, so #[refine] is unnecessary I have a different answer that I will explain below. 3. (Optional) Explain the rationale behind the answers to Questions 1-3. 4. (Optional) Give an example from your own experience which you think supports using implicit or explicit trait refinement.
6.title: Questions
